    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O=S(=O)(O)O"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is the classic textbook example of the Ritter reaction, featuring the reaction of tert-butanol with acetonitrile. Under strong acid catalysis (e.g., sulfuric acid), tert-butanol dehydrates to form the stable tert-butyl carbocation. This carbocation is then trapped by the nitrile, forming a nitrilium ion intermediate, which is subsequently hydrolyzed to the N-tert-butylacetamide product. All reactants and products are simple, acyclic, and clearly illustrate the core transformation: carbocation formation, nitrile trapping, and hydrolysis to an amide.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The use of a simple tertiary alcohol (tert-butanol) as the carbocation precursor and a simple nitrile (acetonitrile) avoids complex structures that could overlap with other named reactions. It specifically avoids arenes (Friedel-Crafts), alkenes (Markovnikov addition variants), or other functional groups that might trigger unrelated reaction family classifications. The transformation is clearly an amidation via a carbocation-nitrile pathway, characteristic of the Ritter reaction."
  }
}
